lazyTrees

Class LazySearchTree<E extends java.lang.Comparable<? super E>>

  • java.lang.Object
    • lazyTrees.LazySearchTree<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E -
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Cloneable

    public class LazySearchTree<E extends java.lang.Comparable<? super E>>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Cloneable
    Binary Search Tree which implements lazy deletion. Each node includes a boolean member called deleted. This member would be set to true if the node has been remove()-d from the tree. During a remove operation in a BST with lazy deletion, the node is marked as deleted instead of physically being removed from the tree. Insert, find, findMin(), findMax() operations are adjusted accordingly. Also provides 'hard' versions of the above methods which consider both deleted and undeleted nodes for debugging purposes. While this makes some operations like remove simpler, it slows down some operations like find(), findMin(), findMax() etc. Implements garbage collection to truly remove all deleted (stale) nodes from the tree.
    Author:
    anuva

      • findMin

        protected LazySearchTree.LazySTNode findMin(LazySearchTree.LazySTNode root)
        Find minimum of the undeleted nodes of the tree. To find the minimum, follow the left children all the way down the tree until we hit a null. If a node has been found but is marked deleted, then check if the root is not deleted since that is the next smallest. If the root is also marked deleted, start looking in the right subtree for the next minimum
        Parameters:
        root - LazySTNodenode of the subtree of interest
        Returns:
        the minimum node that has NOT been deleted.

        Returns:

      • findMax

        protected LazySearchTree.LazySTNode findMax(LazySearchTree.LazySTNode root)
        Find maximum of the undeleted nodes of the tree. To find the maximum, follow the right children all the way down the tree until we hit a null. If a node has been found but is marked deleted, then check if the root is not deleted since that is the next largest. If the root is also marked deleted, start looking in the left subtree for the next largest
        Parameters:
        root - LazySTNode node of the subtree of interest
        Returns:
        the maximum node that has NOT been deleted.
